segments.text: And the beef because the Indians were so prevalent that they'd steal anything that they could get.
The logs up there is where they would put their bedrollers over the day and take them down at night.
That's where they would be put in here.
Grandmother did her work of quilting out here, and it was cool.
He would go in to Austin to get the commodities, and this is more or less of a trading post.
He would have bring back wagon loads of things and supply what he had around here.
Well, over here, you can see that where that's lined up out there, that ridge,
In 1920, my husband and I bought 30 acres of the original Louis Johnson home place, and that is it.
And it came to right where that smokehouse is, right down here.
The rest of it, from here to town, and from here to the highway, was ours.
And just this house, from here to the Bruckner's at that time.
We sold that to President Johnson and moved our cows from there.
But it is quite something else.
My grandmother was brought here as a bride, and I was brought over there as a bride.
So that's how my roots are built.
a little bit deeper than the average person.
And I love it.
And I love the people.
I guess that's why I'm here.
Do they even go back?
I don't know.
How about that time that the Indians nearly got to your grandmother?
Well, she had gone down to the... Well, we dug that hole out down there.
You all saw that big pool of water.
And when we dug it out,
We found lots of cattle and horse bones and things.
That was an open spring that bubbled up.
So we dug it out and irrigated all of that land down there.
But when grandmother lived here, she went down there together, some poke greens for dinner, and bring some fresh water back to the house.
She looked out across the flat over there, or the senderos it's called,
up there and she saw these Comanche Indians coming and she knew that if they got up here that they would kill her babies.
She had two of them.
One was a tiny baby in the cradle in there and the other was about 18 months old.
running around and she had left them here at the house while she went down.
They were asleep while she went down to get the water.
So she left her water and she come running back up here and she pulled her rug back from in front of the hearse and Grandfather had a root cellar down under there.
They kept a lot of their things hid from the enemies.
So she grabbed a diaper
and put around the tiny baby and took the other little one and they crawled down in under this, in this root cellar and pulled the lid over it.
And the Indians came through and they stole everything that Grandfather had gone to Austin to get to go up the trail the next day, next two days rather.
He was to leave the second day after the raid.
She went to the barn and he saw that they had killed the bee and they had taken her saddle and they had taken her horse.
And he came back to the house and he called Eliza and Eliza didn't answer.
He called Eliza and she still didn't answer.
And he went through the house and he thought we didn't have any commodities left, nothing left.
They had cleaned him out.
And he said, well, I guess they've just taken her and taken the babies.
And he looked in the cradle, and there was nothing in the cradle.
And he had his boots on, and he stomped his foot, and he said, Eliza Jane Button, if you're here, you answer me.
She said, yes, Sammy Lee, I'm here.
He said, well, why didn't you answer me before?
She said, Sammy Lee?
Don't you know that an Indian can mimic anything and everything that ever walked?
And how did they?
They didn't know that my name was Eliza Jane Button, and nobody but you did.
And that's the reason I answered you.
So that's when she came out.
She said to me, she said, now, Sammy Lee, I have these two little girls.
And I'm not going to raise them in the wilderness.
You can just take me back to the prairie and you can take these cattle on that Chisholm Trail and say, let me live in peace.
While you're gone, I'm not going to stay up here.
So she went back to the prairie.
She was a little woman, but I want you to know she covered the ground she stood on.
And when she told you that that was enough when you were little, she didn't repeat it the second time.
You knew better.
Okay?
Oh.
I have found something I thought was right good.
But she's hard but true.
I didn't put down my camera, and I intended to do that.
I forgot my county.
Anyway, what county is it in Texas that's larger than the state of Rhode Island and doesn't have a single commercial business in it?
I have forgotten and I had that put down.
Brewster.
Brewster County.
All right.
Only 900 people live there.
They have their own church, their own school, their own post office, and their own commissary.
It's larger than the King Ranch.
And it's the only county in Texas that doesn't have a single gasoline station.
Well, that's it.
I was thinking of gasoline stations then.
So unusual for this day and time.
That's the reason why I put it down here.
Now, one thing about living here, and I know Miss A was talking about this before, but this really was isolated.
We'd gotten here pretty easily and the roads were good and everything, but it was a different story.
in the 1910s and 1920s, Linden worked on the first road that they built into this area.
I don't think that Linden was the only one who worked on it, brother.
I did too.
We had a wagon.
That was before child labor law came into effect.
My daddy had a wagon in Keene, and we had in this old wagon, the bottom of it,
and they had them tapered so we could turn them like that and empty the sand out.
And we hauled sand from the river down there to the first six miles on this road from Johnson City to Miller Creek right out there.
And there was three of us, my sister and Lyndon and I.
And I was the oldest.
Listen, it's no fun to be the oldest of women.
I'll tell you that.
Because he was the largest, and he thought he was boss.
And my dad used to say, now you do this, sister.
You do this, and you keep him in line.
Keep him in line, me, I.
And I got more spankings for it than anything else.
But anyway, we hauled gravel for that.
And then Uncle Sam, actually, we got it.
Actually, it was tops.
They had a lot of loose rock and things along the side.
And they gave London a rake and told him to rake those rocks off down in the bar ditch so they could come along with the Fresno and pick them all off.
Well, he worked a couple days and decided that he could go back to school and do anything to do that.
That's the truth.
That's the real.
Anything else you want to know besides what I haven't told you?
Oh, you know if you want to call somebody a bad name and you want to really, really get to them, just call them a turkey.
That's all you have to do, just call them a turkey.
There's a picture down there in the exhibit center.
where they bought turkeys.
And they were bought, and we'd drive those plastic things, and that's a good name for them, from here to Marble Falls.
And every time a grace offered to fly over the road, what do you think happened?
Yes, they scattered from here to breakfast.
And then you'd have to go and round them up again and get them started out.
And you couldn't drive them in a day's time.
You couldn't drive them in two days' time.
And let me tell you something.
A turkey won't roost in an ordinary tree.
It's got to be the highest tree that they can find.
And you've got to just work them around and around and around that tree to ever get them to roost.
Oh, it
And if you want to get even with anybody, don't call them chicken.
That's a good name.
Call them a turkey.
How long did it take y'all to do that?
Two days and nights.
It will measure about 23 miles.
No, sir, that's not moving.
You can go four miles an hour with a turkey if you'll make him go.
Four miles is a pretty good speed for a turkey, but you don't make him do it.
Miss Cox, you were driving cattle to town when you had the turtle suits, weren't you?
Yes, I was.
She didn't want to tell about the turtle suits.
My daddy made, now this is a long time ago, they farmed kids out just like they go down to the border and get some wetbacks to come in and work.
Well, in this country, they'd farm the kids out like mine.
And so they'd farm those, well...
They said, get those Johnson kids.
Go ahead and tell them.
Get that bunch of Johnson kids.
They're tougher than a boot.
We'll get by with them.
So that's the name we had.
So no use to deny those things.
You'd like to be good, but there wasn't any good things.
And we didn't rob a bank, though, boys and girls.
And we didn't get put in jail.
We got led up to it.
We just didn't get any.
You got as close as you could get.
Just as close as we could get.
That's for seeding chickens and drying them on the river.
I didn't hear that.
It's the first time I've heard it.
You're telling me more than I want to know.
Well, a senior class, it was six of us anyway.
And the six of us, there's three Chomsons.
So...
And one of them, one, wasn't it, Johnson, was Ross, and she was the first cousin of Margaret and I, so we was all kinfolks.
I had made four of us, and the other two had to follow suit every time.
Poor things, they didn't have a chance.
They didn't have a chance.
They didn't have a chance.
They just had to follow along with us, so they did.
And we went out here, and we had plenty of chickens at home, but, you know, it's just fun to see if we can get it out of somebody else's.
And to keep them from hollering, we had to wring their necks.
So we'd kill them as soon as we caught them.
And we had four.
And there was only six of us in the class.
Now, we had four chickens to eat.
But we went down there, and every one of us was designated.
Now, you go get the flour.
You slip the flour out.
You get the salt and pepper.
You get the grease.
You get the pan.
And anybody that failed to bring it, boy,
They got sent back actually, and they were glad to get him.
But anyway, that's how that worked.
And I want you to know we finally took him up a storm, and we heard this car coming.
And you know, cars in those days would scare us to death.
But we heard it coming, and we didn't want the world.
We knew there was something.
Well, this was the district attorney.
Yeah, and he came up.
And he came down there and he asked us where we got those chickens.
Lemon was the spokesman.
He said, well, uh...
He looked at me and started saying, we got him today.
And Kitty said, no, we didn't have him in the cook.
We didn't have him.
So Kitty and I said, that was my cousin.
She...

yeah we got him over at mr ross's and he said good night uncle and he came out of that course and my chickens were all in the pen well all right he's already sunk so we told him where we got him and he gave us a lecture and he told us that well he'd have us before the grand jury the next day
We'd have to, man, what a disgrace we'd draw on our families, but the zillion chickens and these just ruined the reputation of the school.
All of us seniors, and we'd just ruin the reputation of the Johnson City High School seniors by doing anything like that.
Well, we spared the living car out of it.
And sure enough, that's before the grand jury.
And we told them we didn't.
And we were assessed penalty.
paying for them.
And we did.
Of course, it wasn't too much.
But, you know, in those days, a dollar a hen was a whole lot of money.
And it was a whole lot of money for us to get.
And what we did, well, shoot.
We did.
I washed dishes all day in the cafe for a quarter.
trying to save that old man.
Did you even get to finish eating the chicken?
No, we didn't get any of it.
They took it all and just left us.
And I mean, we just spewed and sputtered in our own fat.
Scared to death.
Now, there was one time I said we was right at the jailhouse doors.
I'd rather have been put in jail and listened to that call.
And it happened.
Tell them about the turtle soup.
Well, my daddy had sold these steers to Tom Stripling, who was a big cattle buyer in this country back in 1915 to 1925.
He bought lots of turtle soup here.
And so we lived down the river there, 10 miles, and he sold it round mountain this way about
Well, it's exactly 15 miles to his pens, and so that's 25 miles.

So you drive an old cow just about five, six miles, not over that, an hour, if they drive good, and if you've got the lane and you don't have seat brakes, and you don't have something to scare them with, you get along pretty good, and if you don't, you do.
So we got over there just about...
She told us she had a great long fortune.
She told us, you can take your horse down to the barn.
You can put it in there.
And put your saddle and your blanket over here so you can use that to sleep on it.
Look at Marty.
Look at him.
I thought he was sleeping on an old stinky, wet saddle blanket.
Didn't say anything.

So we put our blanket and our saddle down and went on down and put the horse in the barn and Teddy came on back up to the house and still just worrying me to death about having to sleep on that stinking saddle blanket.
Had an old stinky.
sweaty saddle blanket and got to sleep on it.
You know what I'm talking about.
You missed part of your life.
It really is a loader.
So she called us in and said, I got just something to eat.
She said, don't wash your hands.
I didn't see any place to wash hands.
But I said, where, Mrs. Scribby?
And she said, oh, there's a tin tub right out there in the back closet.
She said, just go out there and wash it.
OK, we went out there and washed our hands in the tin tub.
Come back, went in the house and sat down and gave us a big bowl.
And in front of it was just as clear as crystal.
It looked like that.
But then I said, what is this news?
She says, that's soup.
He says, soup?
And he looked down again and he said, well, just what kind of soup is this?
She said, well, Tuttle soup of course.
It's good for you.
Margaret pushed it back.
I pushed mine back.
She said, well, what in the world is wrong with you gal?
Are you too high-toned to eat Tuttle?
Margaret said, I sure am.
I just can't do this.
And so...
Tom came along and he gave us each one a nickel.
And it was a mile and a half over to the country store.
And we walked over there and got a
A can of five cents of sardines.
Oh, God.
And a package.
Lyndon brought the crackers.
And Marguerite and I bought two cans of sardines, and that was our supper.
Oh, God.
Oh, God.
That's just what I thought.
And hungry.
I was hungry to my heels.
That's what we had.
That's a total soup.
That total soup didn't go down.
Sure it didn't.
Y'all have any questions you want to ask me?
All right, this is something that is off the records, but we talked about this in 1936 from the headless Centennial Parade in San Antonio.
My father was president of the old trail drivers and I rode in that parade.
This year, when the wagon train came through, I got on down here at San Antonio, rode up the air and from here to Kerber.
So I don't know that I'll make the next 50 years that I made this.
I'd bet money on it.
I wouldn't be there trying.
But anyway, that's something that you won't find.
Not too many people can make that claim.
No, that's what I say.
Not too many can do that.
I just wonder how many that were part of that Centennial train did make it to the .
I don't know.
I had no idea.
I was working down at the ranch, down at Cypress Mill, and I mean working, I mean all of it.
She still keeps the ranch going now.
I have double-registered burners, and I'm proud of them.
They're pretty.
And I went down, I was working, I was working down there yesterday afternoon, but anyway, come back in that before it's going to pity.
The telephone rang and said, Ms. Cox, what do you have lined up for this next week?
I said, well, nothing, only just ordinary chores that a person with a place has to take care of.
Why?
Well, would you, do you think you'd be able, are you physically fit to ride a wagon?
I said, what?
So I asked over, do you think you're physically fit to ride a wagon?
I said, well, I'm going to tell you something.
I've ridden in wagons a lot of times.
And they're a lot easier riding than some of these Ford's that I've been in.
So she said, well, what I called for, I want to know if you'd ride in a 16-year-old wagon train.
I said, well, I don't mind that.
You just want me to ride, and I don't have to do anything?
Not a thing.
Well, that was a bunch of baloney I got to do plenty of.
But anyway, I enjoyed every bit of it, and it was worth it.
Of course, they didn't think I could cook, but I can fool you.
I can make good, good sourdough biscuits in an old skillet.
That was something.
No turtle soup.
Is there anything else?
Oh, I don't know whether you, I know that you don't know this.
The jail down here that we have, in the 17 surrounding counties, it's the only one that passed inspection by the state.
And it was built by a man by the name of
Kergy La Pookas Buildout.
Isn't that a name for you?
But anyway, he built that and it was all out of native rock like we have here and native rock that came from right over there.
And it was done by, and it was specified in the order that was sent out that it all be done by native labor.
And it was done by native labor.
And he also built the vault in the courthouse that's down there now, and locked it, and built the lock for it.
And he locked it.
And they gave us a value for it this last, well, I started working on it in last May.
Finally got it through last month.
Yeah, you know, in addition to, since she doesn't have anything else to do, she's involved.
with the Blanco County Historical Society.
Just a little thing.
How many clubs did you tell me who were coming back last spring?
Five?
Yeah, just about five.
Garden Club, Woman's Club.
You and I, your daughters, I'm proud of that.
I think that's worth a whole lot of time now.
Not everything that was left.
You don't have any questions you want to ask them?
This is your chance.
Yeah, I don't know.
Yeah, exactly.
You know, you mentioned that you're, Dave mentioned that you're teaching a course, Lyndon went into education also.
I'm just wondering, what was the main influence for you going into that?
Well, I'll tell you, it's a sad story.
When you're born into a family of nothing but teachers, there's not much salvation for you.
You just have to go ahead and do it.
That's it.
Now, my grandmother Johnson's family, they were music teachers, art teachers, and, of course, they call it home economics, but she was a seamstress.
She taught sewing, principles.
And then regular teachers there.
Then, on my mother's side, the same six and a half, there wasn't any way that we could get out of it.
It's just that or else.
And if you've ever been that else road once with them, you don't want to repeat.
You just go ahead.
I forgot how you said when you married your husband.
How old were you?
Well, I wasn't old enough.
I knew you were young, but I can't remember how old you were.
Well, my mother said I wasn't right behind the ears.
Well, I don't think any.
17-year-old girl really knows what she wants to do to get out of work.
That's the only thing I can tell you she wants to do.
Are you married to get out of work?
Yeah, but they don't know what they're getting into.
They're probably getting more work than they do.
They absolutely do.
They absolutely do.
But, well, you can't tell them anything if you swallow them both.
Now this, this is rippling, but it's the truth before my girls got on it.
We went to church that morning.
Well, my husband had asked me once to watch the door, and I get to show you how little sense you go ahead.
And I feel like now I have a little bit of common sense, but I won't say too much.
But anyway...
Went to church that morning.
I go to church whether I do any good or not, I go.
So when we went in, he said to me, he said, how about us getting married today?
I said, what did you say?
He said, how about us getting married today?
I just turned around and I said, well, brother, what do you know?
Get the license, let's go.
no more give it a thought than nothing under the shining sun, so help me glory.
And I didn't think anything about it.
No, I really didn't.
And he just turned around and left me standing there at the door.
And when it was time to go in, I went on in and sat down.
And they sang Onward Christian Soldiers.
And Owen wasn't there.
I thought, oh, heavens.
He'd gone somewhere else.
I don't know where, but he went there.
And so then the next song they sang, they usually sang three, and then every class went to their room for service.
And they sang, The Half Has Never Yet Been Told.
And I thought to myself, that's a song.
Wonder what our lessons are.
Well, about that time old one walked up.
He didn't stop by where I sit.
He never even looked at me.
His head would be lying up to where that creature's sitting down.
And he said to him, he said, Brother Morgan, I have the license here, and I think that
Ava and I'd like to get married this month.
He said, well, you'll just do it right now.
Oh, yeah.
And that's exactly what happened down that aisle.
He came, he picked me up, he said, are you ready?
I said, with what?
He said, we're going to get married.
I said, well, I told you, I read his viewer.
I didn't have one or two things.
I didn't even have a purse.
I didn't have one thing.
Oh.
And just as he said, I pronounce you Mary Michael, and then Margaret walked in that door of the church.
And he said, oh, no, you can't do that, Ava.
You can't.
